'''Darren Freeman''' (born 22 August 1973) is an English [[association football|football]] manager who manages [[Whitehawk F.C.|Whitehawk]]. He is a former professional player who played as a [[midfielder#Winger|winger]] and [[Forward (association football)|striker]], making over 130 appearances in [[the Football League]] between 1995 and 2001.

==Career==
Born in [[Brighton]], Freeman played in [[the Football League]] with [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], making a total of 134 appearances.<ref name = "postwar">{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player2/darrenfreeman.htm|title=Profile|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Player's Database|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref><ref name = "SB">{{soccerbase|2668}}</ref> He retired from professional football in August 2001 due to injury.<ref name = "tears">{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/archive/2001/08/30/6774511.Tears_of_a_local_hero/?ref=arc|title=Tears of a local hero|accessdate=6 July 2013|date=31 August 2001|publisher=The Argus}}</ref>

{{quote box|quote=He will always be remembered for two feats with the Seagulls <U+2013> scoring a hat-trick in Albion<U+2019>s first ever competitive match at Withdean Stadium, when they beat Mansfield 6-0, and scoring the first goal of the new millennium when he netted in an early kick-off against Exeter on January 3, 2000.<ref name = "manager"/>|width=33%|align=left}}

He returned to non-league football in June 2002 with [[Margate F.C.|Margate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=4526|title=KINNEAR SIGNS FREEMAN|publisher=NonLeagueDaily.com|date=21 June 2002|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/archive/2002/07/08/5128952.Freeman_plays_again/|title=Freeman plays again|accessdate=6 July 2013|date=8 July 2002|publisher=The Argus}}</ref> Freeman also played for [[Lewes F.C.|Lewes]], [[Horsham F.C.|Horsham]], [[Worthing F.C.|Worthing]], [[Glenavon F.C.|Glenavon]], [[Three Bridges F.C.|Three Bridges]] and [[Whitehawk F.C.|Whitehawk]].<ref name = "postwar"/><ref name = "SB"/><ref name = "manager"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/teams/players.php?pid=13237|title=Profile|publisher=NonLeagueDaily.com|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=64880|title=TWO MORE FOR FREEMAN|publisher=NonLeagueDaily.com|date=23 February 2010|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref> Glenavon attempted to sign Freeman on a permanent basis following a loan spell in which he was described as taking the Irish League "by storm."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.questia.com/library/1G1-60642577/football-don-t-be-silly-billy-this-pair-are-staying|title=FOOTBALL: DON'T BE SILLY BILLY!; This Pair Are Staying Put, Hamilton Told|publisher=The People|date=18 January 1998|accessdate=6 July 2013|author=Gordon Hanna}}</ref> Freeman was a player-coach at Three Bridges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/archive/2004/10/22/6710486.County_League__Bridges_release_coach_Freeman/|title=County League: Bridges release coach Freeman|accessdate=6 July 2013|date=22 October 2004|publisher=The Argus}}</ref>

He was appointed sole manager of [[Whitehawk F.C.|Whitehawk]] in May 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=67123|title=FREEMAN TAKES SOLE CHARGE OF HAWKS|publisher=NonLeagueDaily.com|date=26 May 2010|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref> having previously been joint-manager of the club alongside [[George Parris]] since May 2009.<ref name = "manager">{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/4397756.Freeman_joins_Parris_at_Hawks/|title=Freeman joins Parris at Hawks|accessdate=6 July 2013|date=26 May 2009|publisher=The Argus|author=Howard Griggs}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Freeman has two sons, called Leighton and Stacey, with his partner Lorraine.<ref name = "tears"/> His father, called Reg, died in August 2009, and was cited as an inspiration to Freeman's career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/sport/4688138.Freeman_inspired_by_late_father/|title=Freeman inspired by late father|accessdate=6 July 2013|date=17 October 2009|publisher=The Argus|author=Howard Griggs}}</ref>

